After the management has decided what is produced and how many, they are ready to decide where the products should be produced and at which plant will be best for volume and quality of good, keeping in mind the customer demand and satisfaction must be met.  After the location for production of the products has been decided, the next step is managers’ focus on scheduling workloads, and maintenance of equipment. Production is a very important step in the supply chain process.  Every detail is vital throughout the whole process. If every detail is not planned accordingly, it could cost the company a lot of time and money in the long run. For example, I use to work at Wal-Mart and Target retail stores. Both companies have a design, booklet, and process for every entity of the business. There is a designed layout of how an employee’s uniform should look to receiving shipment from trucks. Having outlined processes allow a company to work smoothly without confusion of direction and expectations. 
	The second key element in the supply chain management is supply. Supply is defined as the strategic decisions that should be made to determine the core capabilities of a facility and outsourcing partnerships should grow from these decisions. A company may have many different divisions of production for a single product.  All division consists of different equipment, workers, and specialties. The manager must decide which division is a best fit for the different processes of the product.  Management may also decide to outsource the work to other companies. The core reason a manager would outsource the work to companies is to create velocity. Velocity is the ability to provide quality and flexibility while at the same time reducing costs or maintaining low cost levels.

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign says.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner with a piece of cardboard held above her head, the unsettling message scribbled with Sharpie onto her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian country ruled by a tyrannical militant junta who came into power in 1962 through the act of a coup d’état. In 2007 a number of street protests occurred, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests earned the name “The Saffron Revolution”, christened after the color of the robes that the monks wore. After the first few initial uprisings the public at large began taking an interest in the protests, and while at first the Burmese government begrudgingly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, soon the violence escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries around the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27th, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll rests at 13 killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army some days prior to the official report, is quoted as having said, “Many more people have been killed in recent days than you’ve heard about. The bodies can be counted in several thousand.”

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities taking place in our world, a government’s desire to quash dissent and maintain complete rule over its citizenry has been around for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive ruling over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republic Party.

Some of the most well known examples of these actions are such incidents as the 1989 June 4th protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students all gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular instance ranges wildly, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead to reports let out by the Chinese Red Cross, declaring between 2,000-3,000 dead.  Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began a systematic killing of all Tutsis, as well as political moderates, irrespective of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’, a period spanning several years and several countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington’s legacy in jazz derives in large part from his longevity and, by extension, his creative abilities to shape his orchestra. Ellington’s presence on the piano is subtle in many of the compositions selected for this assignment, but as a composer Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual abilities of band members. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that called on the particular style of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing this, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington’s mastery of the individual players’ sound, as well as how they fit together in a growing ensemble, enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.
The Grove Music dictionary, in discussing Ellington’s sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call in reference to using voice “as a jazz instrument” throughout his career.  This is an early example of Ellington’s use of voice to add texture and color without the hindrance of lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington’s ability to compliment the style of his soloists, something that is evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:
Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice begins smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound towards the end.
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes.
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections.
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.
Tag: Brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.
Ellington’s use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is one example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. 
In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

She had always felt like she needed something. It was this desire that refused to be fulfilled. It started when she was about 14, just getting into a teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she had determined she wanted someone rather than thing. Yet, she had felt no interest in any boys. Some had been attracted to her, gone through the awkward attempts to woo the un-woo-able, but no one appealed to her. She questioned herself often with this strange notion, trying to think of what it was that could possibly cause such a strange thing to happen with a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought up theories, but nothing good enough for her to really speculate on. So she lived life, continually questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually a peaceful thing. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other and oddly enough, arguments with their daughter were very seldom. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality which made her very like-able in combination with the fact she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, attempting to find some new inspiration for her own her, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic as she frantically questioned, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the ground, appearing to be in pain as she continually kept saying "Ow" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her side and put a hand on her to attempt assistance. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital." The words were rushed and squeezed and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother directed her hands and at this moment, the hero of the house was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, set her in the back lying down, and drove.

A visit to the hospital brought scents of disinfectant and sickness, laced with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She carried the injured woman in quickly and started calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered around and someone quickly pulled up a rolling bed and laid her mother down on it. They took her to be immediately looked at, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.
transformed_texts:
I want to help people. I want to work with children who have been hurt. I want to help families who need support. I will study social work so I can do this work.

I want to be a good social worker. I will be kind and fair to everyone. I will do what is right. I will help people build good relationships. I will always learn new things to be a better worker.

I have always wanted to help people. I saw people have problems. Some people hid from their problems. Some people used bad ways to deal with problems. I saw these things in high school and college. I wanted to help. So I studied psychology.

After college, I took a break. One day, I met a young boy. He was scared. He was running away from his parents. They were hurting him. I tried to help him. I talked to the police. I talked to his parents. I saw that these parents did not care for their son.

This made me want to be a social worker. I want to help children like this boy. I want to help families have better relationships.

Being a social worker means fighting for what is right. Everyone is important. But sometimes, people are not treated fairly. I fight for fairness.

In high school and college, I fought for what is right. I did things that showed I was different. I showed people that it is okay to be yourself. I fought against unfairness. I will always fight for what is right.

This paper looks at sleep problems using two ideas: the body's nature and the world around a person. The body idea looks at genes and health. The world idea looks at things like where a person is from, their family, and how much money they have. This paper looks at studies about sleep problems and how they fit with these two ideas. The paper also talks about the good and bad parts of each study.

Sleep problems can be main sleep problems, problems caused by mental health, or problems caused by other things. Main sleep problems are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias. Dyssonmias are hard time falling asleep or staying asleep. Parasomnias are strange things that happen while sleeping. Sleep problems caused by mental health are linked to problems like sadness or anxiety. Other sleep problems can be caused by sickness or medicines.

This paper talks about insomnia, a main sleep problem, and how it fits with the body and world ideas.

The body idea says that sleep problems can be caused by genes or sickness. The brain has parts that control sleep. One part is called the hypothalamus. It has cells that make a chemical called orexin. Orexin helps people sleep and wake up. One study looked at mice and found that a part of the brain called the GABAB receptor helps control sleep. When this part is active, it makes people sleep more. When it is not active, people feel less worried and can sleep better. This study shows that genes and the environment can affect how well people sleep.

The world idea says that sleep problems can be caused by things in a person's life, like where they come from, their family, and their money.  If someone is from a poor family, they may have more sleep problems.

This paper tells about three things about Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition. Next, it talks about how to find out if someone has CAPD. Last, it tells how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a normal classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD, is a problem with how the brain uses sounds. People with CAPD can hear sounds. But their brain has trouble understanding sounds. It is like the brain can not sort words or sounds in a noisy place.


People first talked about CAPD in the 1950s. It was called “auditory imperception”. Some doctors wanted to understand why some children had trouble talking.

CAPD can show up in many ways. A person with CAPD may not be able to hear sounds well in different places. They may have trouble telling sounds apart. They may not be able to hear patterns in sounds. They may not be able to tell if a person is being funny or mean by their voice. One sound may block another sound. They may not be able to understand what they hear. They may not be able to remember the order of sounds.  

To find out if someone has CAPD, a doctor may ask the person questions. They may watch how the person listens. They may give the person tests about sounds.


There is no one test to find out if someone has CAPD. There is no known cause. Some tests give people many sounds at once and ask them to pick out certain sounds. Other tests record sounds in the ear and look at how the brain reacts.

Twelfth Night show us that hiding who you are can be good for a while. But in the end, you must be your true self. Hiding can hurt you because people may not like you if they know the truth. You must choose between being yourself and keeping people happy. Some people will understand, but others will be upset.

Playing pretend with gender is hard. It makes us ask why someone would hide who they are. In Viola's case, she is safe as a man. She says, “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…”(5.1.247-249)

She needs to be a man to be safe. But this also makes her far from other women. She has no one to talk to like her. Then, Olivia thinks Viola is a man named Sebastian and falls in love with her. Olivia says, “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138)

Viola also has feelings for Orsino, but they are hard to express. Orsino says, “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)

Twelfth Night shows us that hiding can help people see their true feelings. Maybe Olivia likes Cesario because he looks like a man. Maybe she likes women, but she does not know it. Olivia likes Cesario and then Sebastian, so maybe she judges people by looks. She says, “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

The German rule over land was bad. This was true for the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. The Germans did bad things to these people.

But German rule was not always bad. It was different in different places. German rule in Africa was like this too.  Some places had good schools. The British found this when they took over German East Africa. In other places, like South West Africa, the schools were not good.

In South West Africa, the German government did not help with schools for the native people. The church helped with schools, but not much. The German government did help with schools for white people.

The schools in South West Africa were not good for the native people. This was different from other places with German rule. This paper will talk about why this was. The paper will talk about the people who lived in South West Africa and the people who ruled them.

There are many books about schools in German Africa. Most books are in German and are old. They talk about how the schools worked. Later books talked about schools in all the German places and how they were different. A good book about South West Africa and East Africa is by Cohen.

South West Africa was a good place to live for white people. It was not too hot or too cold. Many white people lived there.

Popular music has many kinds. It is hard to list them all. Many kinds of music, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have smaller kinds too. Heavy metal is one kind of rock music that is very popular. It started about 40 years ago.

Heavy metal music is different because it has many kinds. It shows many feelings, but dark feelings are common. Many smaller kinds of heavy metal have grown from the main kind. 

There are so many kinds of heavy metal now that it is hard to say what heavy metal is. It uses sounds from other kinds of music. But to understand heavy metal now, we need to understand how it started.

Heavy metal is a movement. It is known for its loud music and dark ideas. It uses more bass, more loudness, more energy, and more drama. People who play in heavy metal bands are good musicians. They show this in their music. Heavy metal is also connected to drugs. In the 1970s, drugs were very popular, and some heavy metal music was made while people used drugs. 

Heavy metal music is dark and strong, which was new in music. Many older kinds of music did not show dark feelings. Some heavy metal music is also influenced by the Romantic period, which was known for its dark feelings. 

One example of early heavy metal is the Beatles song "Helter Skelter." This song is dark and loud. Some people think it is one of the first heavy metal songs. The Beatles made it to show they could be as loud as the Rolling Stones.

Henri Rousseau was a painter.  He painted many dreams. His famous painting, The Dream, shows a woman in a dream. This painting shows Rousseau's dreams for his life as an artist.

He wanted people to see his art and like it.  He wanted to be a famous artist. But, Rousseau had a big problem.  He wanted to paint in his own way. Some art lovers liked to follow rules. Rousseau wanted to break the rules.

Rousseau was born in France in 1844. He worked for the government for many years. He did not learn to paint in school. He was not rich. His wife and many children died. Rousseau started to paint to make himself feel better. He painted pictures of the world he knew.

Rousseau wanted people to like his art. There were many famous artists at the same time. He wanted to be famous too. But, he had to choose. Should he paint like other artists? Or should he paint his own way?

The Dream shows how Rousseau felt about this problem.

Many good people think that good morals and good art are close. They think true things and good things are the same. A writer named John Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” We learn many things in school and life. But we know good morals and good art without learning them.

Good morals and good art try to show us what is true. We study art and morals to understand why something is good. We do not study them to make good art or good choices.

We can talk about art and morals, but we can never fully understand them.  We can talk about a painting, but we can not say why it is good. We say things like, "There's just something about it."

Art and morals are more than words can say. A writer named Flannery O'Connor said, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate."

We feel art and morals deeply. We can not explain them fully.  A writer named Wittgenstein said, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.

I think this feeling is why art and morals are connected.


Literature is special because it has good morals. We learn about values in literature.

Germany is a strong country. It has many different cultures. People in Germany live in many different places. Some live in the mountains. Some live near the sea.  Germany has a long history. Many groups of people lived in Germany a long time ago.

People do not know for sure where the name “Germany” started.  A Roman writer named Tacitus said the name came from a group of people called the Tungrians.  They lived near the Rhine River. The writer Julius Caesar used the word “Germanus” in his books. He wrote about fighting with the Germans. He used the word to talk about people he had not conquered.

Some people think the name “Germany” comes from a spear that the Germans used. Other people think it comes from a word that means “to shout”. The Germans were known for being loud.

A Roman writer named Tacitus wrote about the Germans. He said they were not mixed with other groups of people.  He said that the Germans lived in a wild land with bad weather.

The Romans fought with the Germans for many years. The Romans wanted the land and the goods that the Germans had. The Germans were good fighters.

I look down. I see the bowl. My mind is quiet. I see the details. 
I know about art. A book teach me to see. It say to draw a box. This box make the picture small.
I see the bowl. It is big. It is brown. I want to make art. This is my art. I name it ‘Brown.’
I take a brush. I want to paint. My hand move. The water is clean. It is moving. 
The bowl is stuck. It will not move. I push again. It is hard.
I have a mop. I am tired. I have a tie. It is tight. I look at the bowl. It is bad.
I flush. I flush again. I think. Then I take the paper. I make a big ball. I put it in the water.

Teen drivers have many accidents. This is a big problem in the United States. There are many reasons for this. The teen brain is not full grown. It is not ready for the dangers of driving. Teen drivers also have little experience. 

Young drivers have more accidents when their friends are in the car. They like to drive fast and take risks. 

Some states try to help by giving teens special driver’s permits. These permits have rules, like limits on driving time. But these are not enough.

Teen drivers need more time to learn. They need to wait until they are older and their brains are more developed.  

One expert says 18 is too young to drive. Teens like to take risks. They do this for fun. We need to wait until they are older and less likely to take risks.

If we do not change the rules, many more teens will die in car accidents. There will be many new teen drivers soon. We need to act now to keep them safe. 

We can make new laws. Schools can teach teen drivers. But no one under 18 can drive. Teens can get a special permit first. They can practice with an adult. 

The laws should be the same in every state. This will help protect all teens.

I looked at old movies made by Thomas Edison. I saw all the trick films. There were fifteen of them made from 1895 to 1901. These films use special editing to show tricks. I looked at how these films work. I also looked at some films that were different. Most trick films are made in one place. They use a plain background. The camera does not move. The camera takes long shots or medium shots. Each shot is one part of the film. 

One thing that all trick films have in common is that they are made inside. The camera stays in one place. This is how it was in the theater. It is also how it was in vaudeville shows. This means the people in the films can only move side to side. They cannot walk toward or away from the camera.

For example, in the film “Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel,” the actors move side to side. They do not move toward or away from the camera.

The camera stays in one place. This means the films use long shots and sometimes medium shots. The camera does not use close-ups. This is how it was in the theater. The audience could see the whole play at once. 

Most trick films are short. They are only one minute long. This is because each shot is one part of the film. The films are short and show small tricks. They do not have a story.

Sometimes, what looks like one shot is really many shots put together. This can make it look like someone disappears. Look at the film “The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots.” It looks like one shot, but there is a part where a head is cut off.

John Taylor was from Carolina. He liked the idea of a new country run by the people. Though he worked on a farm, he was also a leader. He liked to speak up. He believed in freedom and the people. He liked farmers the most. He thought farming was the best way to live. He liked this idea so much it changed how he thought about everything. He thought about how the country should be run, about the laws, and even about the courts.

He thought the United States had a chance to make a perfect country. There were no old ways to stop them. They could make a new way to rule themselves. He believed people are born with rights, and all rights are important. If one right is lost, then they are all in danger. These rights should be safe from the government. He said that some call this the “state of nature.” In this state, strong people take what they want. But in a good country, this must not happen.

To make a good country, he said the government must help people be good. He believed in good and bad inside of people. He said the government should help people be good. He said good things help farmers, protect their property, and are not too big. He thought if the government was good, it would work well even if the leaders were not perfect. He said people want to help themselves. This is not bad, but it is bad when people only help themselves and not others. A good government can stop bad things.

Like other people of his time, he wanted to follow the Constitution. He wanted a small government, no bigger than the Constitution said. He thought a big government would be expensive and might take away people’s rights. He didn't want to just read the words of the Constitution, he wanted to know what the writers meant. He thought the Declaration of Independence was more important. It said the country was made up of different states.

This text talks about a project to make people drive less. The project had a problem. People did not use the system as much in the middle of the project.

The project started in the fall. It was hard to say why people used it less in December. Maybe the weather was bad. Maybe students were busy with school. Maybe it was the holidays. 

In January, people still did not use the system much. This was a problem. The project made a special event in March to make more people use it. This worked! More people used the system in March.

The project had another problem. People like to drive. It is easy and free. So, the project gave away prizes.

The prizes were good, but maybe they could have been better. A new bike or car might have made more people use the system.

An ETF is like a basket of stocks. It goes up and down like a single stock. You can buy and sell it on an exchange. ETFs are good like index funds. They have many stocks. But ETFs are more like stocks. You can sell parts of them, borrow money to buy them, and buy just one share. ETFs cost less than regular funds.  But, you must pay money to buy and sell them.

ETFs are good because there are many to choose from. A smart investor looks to see if an ETF really has many different stocks.

We will look at an ETF called IHF. We will look at its top ten stocks. These stocks make up most of the ETF. We want to know if these stocks are the same as the whole ETF.

We will look at the return and risk of the top ten stocks. We will compare them to the whole ETF. Maybe the top ten stocks are better than the whole ETF.

To see if the top ten stocks are different from the whole ETF, we will look at their risk. We will compare the risk of the top ten stocks to the risk of the whole ETF.

Maybe the top ten stocks are a better choice. But maybe they are not. We need to check with numbers.

Edgar Allan Poe liked the poem “Dream-Land” very much. In the poem, Poe use the word “Thulé” two times. It is from the writer Virgil. Virgil wrote about Thulé as an island north of Britain. People thought it was the edge of the world. Virgil did use the word, but Poe like a German writer named Goethe. 

Poe knew a lot about Goethe. A man named Karl Arndt wrote a book about Poe and Goethe. He said that Poe liked Goethe’s poems.

Goethe wrote a very famous play called “Faust”. It had two parts. The first part came out in 1808. The second part came out in 1832, the year Goethe died. In the second part of “Faust”, there is a short poem called “The King of Thulé”.  

The poem is about a king who is very sad. His wife has died. He drinks a lot and misses his wife. He decides to die. He gives his things to his children, but keeps a cup. He goes to a cliff, throws the cup in the sea, closes his eyes, and dies.

The king in “The King of Thulé” is sad like the speaker in “Dream-Land”. The speaker in “Dream-Land” talks about a dark place called Thulé. He is alone and sees dead friends. He sees a dark world with no color. 

Poe used the word “Thulé” twice in his poems. Once in “The Pit and the Pendulum”, and twice in “Dream-Land”. “The King of Thulé” and “Dream-Land” are like poems that go together. 

Goethe was a very important writer. Poe liked him, even if he liked Tennyson more.

A person in California was hurt when they fell in a store. They fell on applesauce. Can the person get money for extra pain and hurt? They say the store manager knew about the applesauce. He did not clean it up.

A judge will not say no right away. To get extra money, the person must show the manager acted badly. The manager knew it was dangerous to not clean up. Many people had fallen before. The manager did not care.

The manager knew about the applesauce. He was told twice. He said he was eating. He did not clean it up for thirty minutes. Then, a person fell.

This person is suing the store. They want money for hurt and extra money for the manager’s bad actions.

In California, people can get extra money if someone acts mean or dangerous. The manager knew the applesauce was bad. He did not care.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. We talked a lot about if Islam is a bad religion.  It is a big question today. After 9/11, the news showed Islam as bad. Now, many people are good to Muslims in America.  Maybe a president like Barack Obama, who has Muslim family, would not have been good four years ago.

The story of Muhammad is interesting. I thought Muhammad was mean. I thought he took over groups and forced them to be Muslim. But the story shows Muhammad as a good man. People liked him and followed him.

Some things in Muhammad's story are like Jesus' story. For example, Muhammad made food grow more. This makes Muhammad look good. But it makes Jesus look less good. It is not fair to copy Jesus!

The story has many stories about people becoming Muslim. But these stories come from other people, not from the people who saw it.  This makes the stories not as good.

The story tries to make Muhammad look good. But history shows he was not always good. I wonder if Muslims know the real story of Muhammad.

The beliefs of Jesus changed much after his life.  Many ideas were added over time.  Today, many people want new ideas.  Old ways are not as important.  Many Christians want to learn more about the true teachings of Jesus.

In the future, many Christians will want to go back to Jesus’s original ideas.  They will remove ideas that were added later. This will take time, but it will happen.

Churches will be strong, but beliefs will be more alike.  There will be less difference between groups.

History shows that things can change.  The Roman Empire was against Christians, but then it became Christian.

America had slavery, but now African Americans have more power.

The Christian religion will change again.  This will go back to the ideas of Jesus.  

People will read Jesus’s words in a new way.

Jesus’s teachings came from Judaism.

Judaism was a strong religion before Jesus.

It had one God and holy books.  The Jewish people had different ideas, but they all believed in the same God.

The book "The Jungle" shows how people can be selfish. They only think about themselves and want to be rich. They do not care about others. The book shows this with the factory owners. They only want to make more money. They do not care about the worker or the pollution. 

Upton Sinclair writes, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This shows how bad the pollution is. The owners do not care about the people or the air.

The owners also do not care about the workers. They want them to work long hours and for little pay. They fire workers without warning and do not help them find new jobs.

There were no laws to protect the workers. This means the owners could treat them badly. The workers had to work fast and in bad conditions. The book says that the workers were like slaves. They had no way to escape.

Many writers use ways to make the reader feel a certain way about things. Some ways work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many ways in *The Great Gatsby*. He puts words together that do not usually go together. This makes the reader feel something. He also uses objects to show feelings.

Fitzgerald uses colors like gold, green, white, gray, and red/pink. He gives these colors special meanings. He then uses them to make the reader feel something about important things.

White and gray mean the same thing: being alike. White is nicer, like a rich person. Gray is older and not as good. Fitzgerald shows this in the beginning of the story. Daisy and Jordan always wear white. Nick wears white clothes to Gatsby’s party. Tom wears a white shirt when he meets Myrtle. Everyone is white, even Catherine. The only time people are not in white is when Nick goes to Gatsby’s party. The colors there are bright. 

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to talk about simple things, too. Nick goes to work on a “white road”. He sees names on a paper. The names are gray. Catherine’s house is white. It is one of many houses that look the same. Fitzgerald uses white and gray for regular people and places. Jordan and Daisy had a white childhood. There are gray cars and gray land. A little boy is gray. An old man selling dogs is gray.

Fitzgerald uses white and gray to mean that something is not important. He does this with Daisy. After a long time, Fitzgerald describes Daisy in white. She is in a white car. Now, Daisy seems less important. She is just something Gatsby wants.

Fitzgerald uses more white to show that Daisy is not important. Her fur has a gray haze. She wears white again before Tom and Gatsby talk.

San Diego is good for farming. The weather is warm and sunny. People grow many things there, like tomatoes, oranges, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people want to buy food from farms that do not use chemicals. There are many farms in San Diego that do not use chemicals. They have long waiting lists. People like to buy eggs and milk from these farms too. Many farms give tours. People can walk on the farm, watch birds, and see how food is grown. This is good for the farm because it can make money.  

Farming without chemicals is good for plants and animals. There are more types of plants and animals. But, farming without chemicals is more work. It costs more money to grow food this way. Farms that do not use chemicals need more workers. They also lose more food.

This farm is in a place called Potrero. It is near a big forest. The farm has many kinds of plants and animals. Some animals are in danger. Some people want to help these animals. This area was used by Native Americans a long time ago. Then, people used it to raise cows and cut wood.

I looked at a place on the internet that sells farms. I looked at programs the government has to help farmers. I want to know how farmers can make money and help animals. I found a farm in the same area. This farm does not use chemicals.

Culture is big in any talk. Culture is hard to say what it is. It is not one thing. It is not the same for everyone. Saying all people from one country are the same is not right. It is good to know about a culture, but it is more good to know how the culture will make the talk go. When we meet people from a new place, we see them in our own way.

To understand a new culture, we can study its past and its ideas. We should not judge a culture or try to change it. We should accept it and work with it. This is very good in a talk, especially if we are not strong in the talk. If we go to a new place, it is good to respect its ways.

Culture is not just about countries. Companies have their own ways too. Some companies work long hours, others not so much. We can see this in how people dress, how they talk, and who they hire. Some companies give money to help others, others do not.

Different companies in America show how many different ways there are to work. Some cultures seem the same, but there are still differences. In every culture, there are good and bad things. Values are very important in culture. Values tell us why people do things. If a culture values saving face, people will not say bad things about their boss in a talk. If a culture values hard work, people will not give up easily in a talk.

It is good to know about a culture before a talk. It is also good to know about the other person in the talk.

People say that God does not exist. This idea is in the Bible, in a book called Psalm 14.  A man named St. Anselm used this idea to talk about God.  Another man, St. Thomas Aquinas, also talked about God. They both thought God was real. We want to know who had the better idea. We will start by saying we think both men are right about God. 

We will look at what each man said. St. Anselm said that we can find God inside ourselves. He said that if we think about God, we know God is real.  He said we do not need to look for proof outside ourselves. This is called faith.

St. Thomas Aquinas said we can prove God exists using logic and what we can see. He said we can see signs of God in the world around us. He gave five reasons why God exists. He said that we can know God is real if we think about how things work.

Neither man gave a perfect answer about God.

Many years ago, a man named Buddha was born. He grew up to be a prince. Buddha left his home and learned much about life. He shared his knowledge with others. This teaching made a new religion called Buddhism. One kind of Buddhism is called Theravada. 

Theravada is old. It is more than two thousand years old. Buddhism looks different now than when Buddha lived. This can be seen in places like Sri Lanka. There, people have a special ceremony with water. Monks and people who are not monks take part. This is important to them, even though Buddha did not teach about it. There are many changes like this, from small things to big things.

The Theravada Buddhists have changed over time. This is because of things from inside and outside their religion. Some things are good, and some are bad. 

We will use special words to talk about these things. Inside things come from Buddhists. Outside things come from people who are not Buddhists. Bad things hurt Buddhism. Good things do not try to hurt Buddhism.

First, we need to know about the basic ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists believe in three things: Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the teaching of Buddha. It is in books called the Tripitaka. The books have three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. 

The Sutta Pitaka has stories Buddha told. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks. The Abhidhamma Pitaka talks about deep ideas in Buddhism. These ideas are like no soul, life is full of suffering, and everything changes.

 Buddhists want to stop the cycle of birth and death. This is called Sansara.  They want to stop wanting things, being angry, and being confused. This is how they become enlightened. 

The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for living. People who are not monks have five rules. Monks have many more. The most important idea in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. First, life has suffering. Second, our wanting things causes suffering. Third, suffering can stop. Fourth, there is a way to stop suffering.

The United States and Mexico had a big fight for many years. This fight went on for fifty-seven years, from 1836 to 1893.  

The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War. This war was from 1846 to 1848. The United States won the war. The United States took Texas and land in the southwest. 

There were many other fights between the two countries. These fights stopped just before World War One. 

The two countries had different beliefs and ways of life. They also wanted the same things. This made them fight.

This is like other countries that are close together. Countries that share a border often fight. 

The United States and Mexico are like other countries that fight. The United States has had big problems with Mexico and Cuba. Other countries in Latin America have had good relations with the United States. 

Religion was a big problem between the two countries. The United States did not like Catholicism. This is like the Cold War when the United States fought against communism. In the Cold War, the fight was about ideas. In the fight between the United States and Mexico, the fight was about religion.  

The United States and Mexico did not like each other because of their past. The English and Spanish had fought long ago. This made it hard for the United States and Mexico to be friends.

There were many fights between the two countries. Most of the fights were about land. Bad men from the United States would go into Mexico and steal things.

The fight between the United States and Mexico stopped when Mexico needed the United States. The United States wanted to help Mexico’s economy.

Fifteen years ago, I got very sick. I did not know what was wrong. I was a nurse. I chose this job for safety. People always need nurses, I thought.  My dream was to be a scientist or a journalist, but I chose nursing.

Then, I was sick. I was 46 and single. I had no money. I could not work. I am still sick. After fifteen years, I have nothing. I live on Social Security. Every day is hard. I am not safe or secure.

I know one thing is true: I could not do this without my family and friends. When bad things happen, you need help.

There will always be problems. We cannot plan for everything. Sometimes we need help from others.

We must not trust the government too much. It is broken. I want Americans to trust each other. Help each other. Ask for help when you need it. 

Some people say we built America on strong, independent people. But the people who came here in the past helped each other. They shared food and helped each other. 

Be prepared. I am. I have supplies for emergencies. I have food, water, and tools.

But also, get to know your neighbors.

Why do living things change over time? Are there limits to how they change? In 1917, D’Arcy Thompson said that we do not yet know how to use math to describe even simple living things. This is still true today.

But now, math is used to study how shells grow and change. (Raup and Stanley, 1981) We are using math and experiments to learn how shells change over time. We took pictures of different kinds of shells and used a computer program to make new shell shapes. This helps us understand how shells can change.

A shell is like a tube that spins around. Each spin is called a whorl. The center of the spin is called the columella. The size of each whorl can change. The line between whorls is called a suture. The biggest whorl is the last one, called the body whorl. All the whorls except the last one are called the spire. The tip of the spire is the apex. The opposite end is the base. The animal lives inside the shell and comes out through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells from different angles. The usual way is to look at the aperture, the opening, and the apex at the top.

To count whorls, look at the shell from the top. Find the first suture and draw a line. Count the whorls from this line.

A shell builds up over time. Each time a new part is added, it is like a new opening. We can track the path of the opening and use math to describe it. We can then change the math to see how the shell might grow differently.

Indonesia has a problem.  Many babies and young children die.  This has not changed for ten years.  Indonesia is good at helping people with clean water and good toilets. But, they need to do much better at helping mothers and children stay healthy.

Indonesia is doing better at getting skilled workers to help at births. But, many of these workers are not doctors. They cannot help if a birth is difficult.  This is why so many mothers die from bleeding after birth.

Fewer children get help from doctors when they are sick with diarrhea. 

Indonesia also needs to help more mothers after they have a baby.

Doctors do not do enough cesarean sections. This is a special surgery to help babies born in difficult ways.  

Doctors do more cesarean sections in cities, but not in villages.  This means people in villages do not get the same care.  

Poor people have a hard time getting help. They cannot pay for care.

Indonesia needs to decide what to do. Do they need new programs for mothers and babies? Or do they need to make the whole health system better? 

New programs are good because they help one problem at a time.  But, this can mean other problems are ignored. Also, many programs are not working well together. This makes things more complicated.

Victorian books are known for many small details. They show a lot about the rich people of the time. Two books from this time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange parts, things not often seen in other books from that time. This helps the people in the stories feel more real. We learn more about why they do things and how they feel.

One part from Oliver Twist shows this:

“He had many strange thoughts. He felt like he was still with Sikes and Crackit. They were arguing loudly. He could hear their words. Then he looked around and saw he was talking to them. Suddenly, he heard gunshots. People were shouting. Lights flashed. Everything was loud and crazy. Someone took him away quickly.”

(Dickens, 220)

Both books use mystery often through dreams or dreams like states. But the dreams are different in each book. In Oliver Twist, these strange things show us about Oliver. They show us what hurts him and what he knows about what is happening around him. When Oliver is shot, he remembers it in a dream. He is trying to find help. 

The story shows that Oliver has no control over what is happening. He is very sick. The shooting hurts him. He does not feel the “unseen hand” taking him away. He feels only pain, fear, and sadness.

The shooting makes us wonder who is to blame for Oliver’s misfortune. It was not his fault. This shows that Oliver has no control over his life. He cannot even try to change what is happening, not even when he is in danger.

This part makes us think that Oliver is giving up. Fagin, a bad man, is breaking him. He is making Oliver feel hopeless. Oliver would try to do something if he could, but he feels like he can’t.


“The day passed – day? It was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its awful quiet and short in its passing hours.”

I worked in a school program a few years ago. I helped young students with school work. I was good at helping with reading and English. 

A teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had big problems reading. Some letters he knew, some he did not. It was strange. Adrian spoke English well. He was from a family where Spanish was spoken. 

One day, Adrian's mother came to the school. She did not speak English. I used my small amount of Spanish to talk with her.  Then I understood. Adrian could read, he just did not know the English letters well.  

I tell this story about Adrian to show a problem in schools. Many students, like Adrian, have trouble with language.  We must help them.

There are ways to help. One way is to teach in two languages. This helps all students.

Some people think teaching in two languages is wrong. They think it wastes time and money. This is not true. 

We need to teach in two languages more. We need people who speak two languages to help students.

Many people learn about the big world when they are young.  Some go to church or temple.  Some think about this world alone.  Some believe what their parents believe.  Some do not.  People choose how they feel about this world.  They want to find the light and know what is right.

My father liked cardinals. We sat on our porch. It was raining. We smoked. The rain made noise on the roof. He looked at the rain. He seemed sad. He was thinner. His hair was gone.  He did not look at me. I felt bad. I did not know what to say. I hugged him. I sat close. We looked at the rain. 

My father died in December. He was sick.  The doctors said he would not live long. He died five days after my birthday.  I did not want to watch him die. I went to bed. I did not want to see his life end. I wanted to remember him when he was strong.  I knew he would not want me to see him die. 

No one called me.

The word "Gothic Novel" is strange. It mixes old things with new things. This is what Ian Watt says in his book, *The Rise of the Gothic Novel*.  People talk about Gothic stories in many ways. Some say they are not good.  Others say they are very good. Some say they are not deep. Others say they make people feel great things, like fear and awe. The first Gothic story was *The Castle of Otranto* by Horace Walpole.  Walpole used ideas from old stories and new stories to make something new. He used old ways of acting and new ways of writing about nature.  He called his story "A Gothic Story."

The Gothic story uses ideas from old stories about castles, knights, and ghosts. Even when *The Castle of Otranto* came out, the word "Gothic" was used for many things. People thought of it as old-fashioned. They liked new things better. But the Gothic story was new because it let readers see inside the minds of the characters. 

One big idea in Gothic stories is chivalry. Chivalry was about training good knights.  Writers liked to talk about chivalry because it meant being brave, honest, and kind. The writers thought that people were not like that anymore. They used chivalry to make the old past seem better. They wanted to make the present better too.

Walpole wrote *The Castle of Otranto* when England was in trouble. He was worried about the future. He may have thought that people were not as good as they used to be. In his story, a character named Frederic is a good example of a chivalric hero. He is a prince who has suffered and is brave. He is everything a knight should be.

Supply chain managing is how goods go from a customer order to the customer. It starts with the raw things needed to make the goods. Then, the goods are made, sent out, and given to the customer.  

A man named Keith Oliver first said the words "supply chain managing" in 1982. He said it is about planning, doing, and watching over all the steps so customers get what they want, fast and well. 

There are six big parts to supply chain managing: making, getting things, keeping things in stock, where things are, moving things, and sharing information. Managers use these parts to make good things happen for customers.

Making is the first part. It is the start of everything. This part says when, why, where, and how things are made. Managers need to know what customers want. They look at the market to see what people want.  Once managers know what people want, they decide what to make and how much. Then, they decide where to make it. They look for the best place to make the goods, a place that can make lots of good things and keep customers happy. After that, managers plan how much work to do and how to keep the machines working. Making is very important. Every detail matters. If things are not planned well, it can cost a lot of time and money later.

Getting things is the second part. It is about making smart choices about how to make things and who to work with. A company might make some parts in one place and other parts in another. Managers decide which place is best for each part. They might also choose to give some work to other companies. This is called outsourcing. Companies do this to make things faster and cheaper.

Ellen Page, star of the movie Juno, is on a street. She holds a sign. The sign says, “Hitler is alive in Burma.” Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. A strong group controls Burma. They took power in 1962.

In 2007, many people in Burma protested. Monks led the protests. People called these protests “The Saffron Revolution” because of the monks’ robes. At first, the government let the monks protest. But then, the protests became dangerous. The army attacked the monks.

Journalists were also in danger. One Japanese journalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed in 2007. He was just covering the protests.

This is not new. Governments have always tried to stop people from speaking out. In the Roman Empire, emperors said they were chosen by gods to rule. In Japan, emperors are believed to be gods.

There have been many bad things happen in history. In 1989, people protested in Tiananmen Square, China. The government used force against the protesters. Many people died.

In the 1990s, there was a genocide in Rwanda. Hutu people killed many Tutsi people. This was a very bad time.

Hitler’s Germany killed many Jewish people. This was also a terrible event.

Duke Ellington is known for good music. He made music for many years and was good at working with his band. Ellington played the piano, but he was a good writer of music too. He made songs that showed off the skills of each player in his band. Ellington made rules for how the music would go. This let the solo players do their own thing. He also made songs where all the players had to play together in a special way. This made the music sound good as a whole. Because Ellington knew how each player sounded and how they worked together, he made some of the best jazz music ever.
